I felt we should have chased this. The mistake was losing wickets at regular intervals, we needed partnerships and they came too late for us. However, plenty of games left. Such things happen

formatValue: Mohammad Shami | Player of the Match:

commText: B0$ Our bowlers were amazing. Our batters struggled but credit to the way Shami bowled. Credit to the way Aman and Ripal played from then on to get up that score. We just find ways to lose wickets in clumps, I always hate it when there's a run out. I don't know what's happening with our batting. We tried playing positively today with the bat, didn't come off. We then wanted to come out and swing the ball, get early wickets. Khaleel did well after coming back from injury, and Ishant is forever getting younger. I was nervous when Tewatia was going off, he has a reputation for that kind of stuff. Anrich is our most consistent death bowler, but couldn't get it right today. But Ishant was so clear with what he wanted to execute for us.

commText: B0$ I keep practicing in the nets. We practice bowling we the new ball, but at the same time we do practice bowling wide yorkers, and today the hardwork paid off, I just backed myself and bowled wide yorkers. When you are preparing yourself in the nets we plan to certain batsmen as to what to bowl and it is all about executing it every single time, back yourself and believing in yourself. I played enough cricket him (Tewatia), so was just having fun with him. I knew I had to double bluff him otherwise we know what he can do with the bat. We (The bowlers) don't think about the target, it is just about executing the plans. From hereon we hope to carry the momentum, keep going forward and hope for the best.

B0$(On the last few overs) We would have taken 129 on any given day. Just lost a couple of wickets and in the end, Rahul got us back in the game. I tried my best in the end but it was not to be. ( On the discussion with Abhinav Manohar) We were hoping to get couple of big overs in the middle but we couldn’t get rhythm. It was new for Abhinav as well and it boils down on how I could not finish the game. Full marks to the bowlers and full ownership I couldn’t finish it. Wicket was good enough, it was wicket pressure. They bowled really well, 10 overs for 80 we would have taken. In the end, Rahul got us in the game, otherwise they were quite ahead. We lost this game because I couldn’t get my rhythm. (On Mohammed Shami’s brilliant bowling) I feel sorry for him, if you bowl like that, and restrict a team to 129 and still not win, the batters disappointed. I don’t think the wicket did a lot but full credit to him. It is still lots of games left, we will take all learning from this game and move on. All these things keep happening, that’s the beauty of IPL. We are still on top of the table but we still need to play good cricket.

B0$ Nick Knight during the pitch report reckoned this would be a flat deck where 180 would be the par score. How wrong was he, and how wrong would most of us have been at the halfway stage when Delhi Capitals scampered their way to 130 runs, after reeling at 23/5 at one stage. With their backs to the wall, the Capitals came out fighting and outfought the champions... They got the perfect start with a wicket maiden from Khaleel, and then Nortje dismissed the other opener Shubman Gill. Vijay Shankar was deceived by a top quality Ishant Sharma knuckle ball, and then David Miller was out playing an uncharacteristic shot to be dismissed for zero. GT found a way back through skipper Hardik and Abhinav Manohar, and they batted out the tough stages, but ate up too many balls. Axar and Kuldeep kept things quiet as the asking rate kept rising, but both GT batters couldn't connect despite their best efforts. However, there came a sting in the tale as Rahul Tewatia walked out and smoked three consecutive sixes, but it wasn't to be his night. It was to be the night of a forgotten man of Indian cricket, as Ishant Sharma held his nerve to defend 12 off the last over and give Delhi a victory. A confidence boosting victory for DC, thanks to some quality, energetic captaincy from Warner who was ably backed by his bowlers. Over to the presentations...

This was wide full toss, Rashid takes a big swing but slices it behind. The man from backward point runs back to stop the boundary, wouldn't have mattered even if it was four... Delhi Capitals win by 5 runs!!
One ball, 7 runs. Super over anybody?
Ishant to Rashid Khan, 2 runs, wide yorker, Rashid slaps it through point where Rossouw makes a diving stop to his right. Saves a couple of runs...
B0$: Really impressed with the calmness of David Warner is such tense situations!

commText: B0$ DC have done well to recover from dire straits but they are still well below par on a track which is decent to bat on. What an absolute dream spell we have witnessed from Shami! His exhibition of top class swing bowling broke the backbone of DC in the powerplay itself. It all started with Salt's downfall for a golden duck. Warner was sold down the river by Garg but the rest of the batters were all at sea against Shamis moving balls. That led to DC reeling at 23/5 within the powerplay. When you are in such a precarious position, it hits you psychologically. Axar and Aman started the rebuilding work but they had to play cautiously. They stitched 50 off 48 balls and then the former fell to Mohit Sharma. The latter kept going and scored his maiden IPL Fifty and Ripal Patel also played a handy cameo down the order. But, the early demolition from Shami means that GT are in the driver's seat. Should be a walk in the park for GT but can the visitors effect a twist in the tale? Join us shortly for the chase..

B0$ Hello and a warm welcome to game 44. Its B1$. There's slight chance that both these sides may remain at the same spot irrespective of the result tonight. While the Titans would eye a win to inch closer to the play-off puzzle, the Capitals would be aware that they just cannot slip up any further. A loss might seriously hamper their play-off chances. To put it mildly, they just cannot afford a loss. With 2 wins from last 3 games, DC will be relieved to have found a winning combination and up against them are a team that won a hat-trick of games and nearly have one foot into the playoffs. Can the boys from Delhi stop Hardik's Titans? We shall know in a while...

B0$   
   
It's David vs Goliath - Round 2 of the 2023 Indian Premier League. Goliath did swat David aside in the first round almost a month ago and will head into this contest as the favourite once again. Gujarat Titans have been on a great run ever since Kolkata Knight Riders shocked them at home. The defending champions have won four out of their last five games and three of those have come away from home. They will return to familiar territory now in search of their fourth straight win to take on bottom-placed Delhi Capitals, a side that just looks destined for the wooden spoon.   
   
DC finally looked like staging a pretty good comeback after losing their first five games. Having won two in a row post that, they were definitely favourites to make it three in three before a batting collapse ensured they suffered a demoralising loss. It's certainly not easy to bounce back from a defeat such as that one especially against a side that has just been continuing to find ways to win from difficult situations since making their bow last year. Titans continue to find new heroes to bail them out and churn out wins whereas even an all-time classic allround performance from Mitchell Marsh couldn't help DC get over the line against Sunrisers Hyderabad.   
   
DC would certainly want more players putting their hands up, beginning with their skipper David Warner. He was bowled for a first-ball duck against his former franchise but had scored runs prior to that, albeit not at a pace he is renowned for scoring at. The conditions in Ahmedabad have been batting friendly and Warner should fancy himself to get going again. But that Indian middle order barring Axar Patel has just not clicked. A promotion for the left-hander might help but David still needs a lot of boxes to be ticked in order to slay Goliath.
